## Issue description
When implementing "diamond" multiple inheritance schemes, any method defined on the common virtually inherited class causes segfaults whenever any class method is called.  If there are no methods on the virtual class, then no issues arise.

## Reproducible example code
C++ Code
```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

class AnimalI {
public:
    virtual int legs() const = 0;
};

class DogI : public virtual AnimalI {
public:
    virtual int bark() const = 0;
};

class Animal : public virtual AnimalI {
public:
    int legs() const override {
        return 2;
    }
};
class Dog : public Animal, public DogI {
public:
    int bark() const override {
        return 0;
    }
};

std::shared_ptr<DogI> makeDog(){
    return std::make_shared<Dog>();
}

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_MODULE(segfault_example, m) {

    py::class_<AnimalI, std::shared_ptr<AnimalI>>(m, "AnimalI")
    .def_property_readonly("legs", &AnimalI::legs, "Method 1")
    ;

    py::class_<DogI, AnimalI, std::shared_ptr<DogI>>(m, "DogI")
    .def_property_readonly("bark", &DogI::bark, "Number of barks")
    ;

    m.def("make_dog", &makeDog, "Make dog");

}
```
Python Code
```
import segfault_example
dog = segfault_example.make_dog()
print dog.legs # this causes segfault

```

